    <item>
      <title>Re: Competitive, Content, Raiding Server (work in progress)</title>
      <link>http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq/board/message?board.id=Progression&amp;message.id=16648#M16648</link>
      <description>I started playing EQ in 2000.&amp;nbsp; Back then, you had to race for mobs.&amp;nbsp; Because you had to race for mobs, it made it that much more exciting.&amp;nbsp; I remember competing with a rival guild for Klandicar for an ST key.&amp;nbsp; Neither of us had a full raid force there, and ppl were still straggling in, but we had to pull or they would, so we did.&amp;nbsp; We wiped.&amp;nbsp; Then they pulled after we wiped, and wiped too.&amp;nbsp; So we pulled again, and wiped again.&amp;nbsp; Then they pulled again, and killed it.&amp;nbsp; They ended up getting the ST key.&amp;nbsp; This kind of a competition is much more fun for me than if we both just showed up, said hi, zoned into our instances, and zerged Klandicar until he was dead.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;When there is no risk of losing the mob to another guild, there is not nearly as much satisfaction when you actually kill it.&amp;nbsp; When you're fighting a mob with another guild breathing down your neck, and you manage to kill it, that's a rush.&amp;nbsp; You can say FU to the other guild and enjoy passing out your loot.&amp;nbsp; There is an intense rush of adrenaline when you're fighting, because you know if you lose, the other guild will kill the mob.&amp;nbsp; That leads to a much greater sense of accomplishment when you actually kill it.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Also, it places a greater emphasis on playing skillfully.&amp;nbsp; If you can show up at a mob and just attempt it 10x, 20x, 100x until it dies, then your guild might suck, but you'll still kill the mob eventually with dumb luck.&amp;nbsp; You might **SMURF** up a bunch of times, but it doesn't matter if you do, you just try again.&amp;nbsp; When there are other guilds and there is competition, you **SMURF** up, and you lose the mob.&amp;nbsp; It's a much better test of skill.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Finally, instancing is a step away from mmorpg.&amp;nbsp; The point of mmorg's is that there is a persistent world that all characters can interact with and change.&amp;nbsp; Instancing is just a step back from that, making the world less multiplayer, segregating people into small groups.&amp;nbsp; If you extend instancing as far as you can, you end up with people playing alone on their own computers.&amp;nbsp; Instancing is a step backwards in mmorpg's, not forwards.&lt;br&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</description>
      <pubDate>Fri, 02 Jun 2006 20:32:39 GMT</pubDate>
      <author>Ammelen</author>
