    <item>
      <title>Re: Competitive, Content, Raiding Server (work in progress)</title>
      <link>http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq/board/message?board.id=Progression&amp;message.id=16653#M16653</link>
      <description>&lt;DIV&gt;"I started playing EQ in 2000.&amp;nbsp; Back then, you had to race for mobs.&amp;nbsp; Because you had to race for mobs, it made it that much more exciting.&amp;nbsp; I remember competing with a rival guild for Klandicar for an ST key.&amp;nbsp; Neither of us had a full raid force there, and ppl were still straggling in, but we had to pull or they would, so we did.&amp;nbsp; We wiped.&amp;nbsp; Then they pulled after we wiped, and wiped too.&amp;nbsp; So we pulled again, and wiped again.&amp;nbsp; Then they pulled again, and killed it.&amp;nbsp; They ended up getting the ST key.&amp;nbsp; This kind of a competition is much more fun for me than if we both just showed up, said hi, zoned into our instances, and zerged Klandicar until he was dead.&lt;BR&gt;When there is no risk of losing the mob to another guild, there is not nearly as much satisfaction when you actually kill it.&amp;nbsp; When you're fighting a mob with another guild breathing down your neck, and you manage to kill it, that's a rush.&amp;nbsp; You can say FU to the other guild and enjoy passing out your loot.&amp;nbsp; There is an intense rush of adrenaline when you're fighting, because you know if you lose, the other guild will kill the mob.&amp;nbsp; That leads to a much greater sense of accomplishment when you actually kill it.&lt;BR&gt;Also, it places a greater emphasis on playing skillfully.&amp;nbsp; If you can show up at a mob and just attempt it 10x, 20x, 100x until it dies, then your guild might suck, but you'll still kill the mob eventually with dumb luck.&amp;nbsp; You might **SMURF** up a bunch of times, but it doesn't matter if you do, you just try again.&amp;nbsp; When there are other guilds and there is competition, you **SMURF** up, and you lose the mob.&amp;nbsp; It's a much better test of skill.&lt;BR&gt;Finally, instancing is a step away from mmorpg.&amp;nbsp; The point of mmorg's is that there is a persistent world that all characters can interact with and change.&amp;nbsp; Instancing is just a step back from that, making the world less multiplayer, segregating people into small groups.&amp;nbsp; If you extend instancing as far as you can, you end up with people playing alone on their own computers.&amp;nbsp; Instancing is a step backwards in mmorpg's, not forwards.&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;BTW, when I played during Kunark/Velious/Luclin, training, ks'ing and the like were pretty rare.&amp;nbsp; You had competition with 2 guilds trying to pull a mob first, but first aggro was generally respected.&amp;nbsp; You also had a lot of cases of one guild waiting for the previous one to wipe, then killing it over their corpses.&amp;nbsp; Training wasn't a big problem though, people just didn't really play that way on Vazaelle."&lt;BR&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;I remember the rush to kill targets in velious very well.&amp;nbsp; I started shortly after kunark and was the first Iksar sk to 60th on Bertox.&amp;nbsp; MANY times my guild and another guild would begin forming and buffing for a kill at the same time.&amp;nbsp; Usually we just had to be a little patient as the rest of our forces got ported to the zone.&amp;nbsp; The first side to pull would do it out of nervousness and wipe since the healers werent full mana or tanks werent fully buffed.&amp;nbsp; Many times we would pick up a King Tormax as he was wandering back to spawn after the op force wiped at WL zoneline.&amp;nbsp; And you are right, most people did respect the initial aggro rules.&amp;nbsp; Some jerks would take it to extreme and run the target in circles till their groups arrived...&amp;nbsp; Sorta bends the rules too far.&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;In any&amp;nbsp;case, here is one possible solution to the lack of competition for specific spawns:&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;[Once a raid kills a flag mob in their instance, it immediately adds a lock out timer equal to the spawn time of the mob on that particular instance for ALL players on the server.&amp;nbsp; So when a guild kills Nagafen in their raid it would send out a serverwide message "&amp;lt; guildx &amp;gt; has slain Nagafen!" And everyones expedition window now has a lockout timer showing exactly when that instance can be started again.]&lt;BR&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;BR&gt;You could take it further by having any existing Nagafens in open instances despawn immediately.&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;If this was added in along with the rest of my suggestions the very real possibility of losing your kill to another guild would still&amp;nbsp;exist.&amp;nbsp; And it would lighten the load on instance servers to an extent.&lt;/DIV&gt;</description>
